      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Pump Pressure-Rise Benchmark Against FDA Loop Measurements",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-generic-pump-experimental-rh",
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": "https://uofa.net/synth/activity/pressure-validation-run-2024-09"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/vr-shear-stress-distribution",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Wall Shear Stress Distribution Validation Against Particle-Image Velocimetry Data for the FDA Generic Centrifugal Pump at 2500 RPM and 6 LPM",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-generic-pump-experimental-rh",
      "description": "Detailed PIV-based validation of the near-wall shear stress field predicted by the k-omega SST turbulence closure. Experimental data were acquired at the FDA's Center for Devices and Radiological Health using a scaled acrylic model of the generic centrifugal pump geometry. The CFD mesh consisted of 14.2 million polyhedral cells with five prism layers at all wetted surfaces, yielding a mean y+ of 0.9. Simulations were run in ANSYS Fluent 2023R1 under steady-state MRF conditions with second-order upwind discretisation. Predicted shear stress magnitudes agreed with PIV measurements to within 8.3% RMS across the impeller sweep region and within 12.1% in the volute tongue zone, both within the acceptance threshold of 15% established in the validation plan. Blood damage scalar transport was post-processed using the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model integrated along massless particle trajectories seeded uniformly at the inlet. The resulting normalised index of hemolysis (NIH) prediction of 0.0023 g/100 L was consistent with the experimentally measured NIH of 0.0027 g/100 L (relative error 14.8%), confirming that the model captures the dominant hemolytic exposure pathways under CPB operating conditions. This result was accepted by the credibility assessment team as satisfying the MRL 2 output-comparison requirement."
    }
  ],
